\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 1: Separability and symmetry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Often, separability of the solutions is a consequence of symmetry.
 In this problem, you will show this for the case of continuous translational
 symmetry: a PDE that is invariant under translation in 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, suppose that we have the operator 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{A}=-\frac{1}{w(x,y)}\nabla\cdot c(x,y)\nabla
\]

\end_inset

for real coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $c,w>0$
\end_inset

 that are invariant in 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 We also have a 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-invariant domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 which is an infinitely long cylinder (not necessarily circular) parallel
 to the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 axis with some 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-invariant cross-section; equivalent, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 could be described as the where 
\begin_inset Formula $s(x,y)<0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-invariant function 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 whose contour 
\begin_inset Formula $s(x,y)=0$
\end_inset

 gives the boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 Under the boundary condition 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x,y,z)|_{\partial\Omega}=0$
\end_inset

, this operator is self-adjoint under the inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle u,v\rangle=\int_{\Omega}w\bar{u}v$
\end_inset

.
 We wish to to find the eigenfunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}u=\lambda u$
\end_inset

 in a 
\emph on
separable
\emph default
 form 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x,y,z)=v(x,y)Z(z)$
\end_inset

.
 As claimed in class, it turns out that 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(z)$
\end_inset

 always has the same form 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-ikz}$
\end_inset

 for bounded solutions of 
\emph on
any 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset


\emph default
-invariant problem.
\end_layout

